The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New York, Aug. 11: Shares on Wall Street retreated today in the wake of the announcement by the US Federal Reserve that it will buy government debt and as new trade figures suggested a slowdown in US growth. In early afternoon, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 226.06 points, or 2.12 per cent, while the Standard amp; Poors 500-stock index dropped 28.42 points, or 2.54 per cent. Nasdaq fell 65.02 points, or 2.86 per cent. The decline was broad-based, led by basic materials, band and industrial shares.                             
	 Mumbai, Aug. 11:           
	g and Manufacturing Co Ltd today said it was yet to decide on whether to sell its ailing polyester plant or continue with the business. There is no transaction on sale of the polyester stable fibre business as reported by the press, chairman Nusli Wadia said. The company board is examining various options.                            
	 New Delhi, Aug. 11: Asim Dasgupta, head of the state finance ministers panel on goods and services tax  today met finance minister Pranab Mukherjee and is understood to have discussed the revised draft of the constitutional amendment bill on GST.                            
	 New Delhi, Aug. 11: JSW Steel is in discussions with several domestic steel producers for floating a joint venture to acquire overseas coking coal properties. The company is in talks with Steel Authority of India Ltd, Rashtriya Ispat Nigam and Jindal Steel amp; Power Ltd, JSW Steel vice-chairman Sajjan Jindal said.                             
	 New Delhi, Aug. 11: The Centre will consider requests for the setting up of special economic zones (SEZ) on September 16 against the backdrop of the revised direct tax code that proposes to do away with the existing duty benefits to new units.                             
	 New Delhi, Aug. 11: Air India has asked Boeing to raise the compensation for a delay in the delivery of B787 Dreamliner planes to $840 million from $710 million sought earlier.
                                                                                                                          
